Class AnyView

  • java.lang.Object

  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Any, Facade, ListenerAdaptee, UIFacade, Composite, EventGenerator, EventListener, Map, Orderable, Vectored, Serializable, Cloneable
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    AbstractButtonGroup, AnyCAction, AnyCDockable, AnyComponent

    public abstract class AnyView
extends InstanceHierarchyMap
implements EventGenerator, EventListener, UIFacade, ListenerAdaptee
    A view of data in the node space. This class provides base functionality for picking up events from the process node space and dispatching them for processing defined in sub-classes. Typically, sub-classes will wrap a delegate object, for example a GUI component, and act as an interface between the Inq event system and that object.

    This class also provides this functionality on a general basis to bind node events to a Java Beans property. A relevant node event will cause the property to be set with the new data value. Unlike specific view functionality, Java Beans is generic and no sub-class implementation is required.

    In a similar way, any Java Beans events that the delegate object supports can be listened for and dispatched to Inq EventListener instances, for example button action events.

      • getProperty

        public Any getProperty(Any property)
                throws AnyException
        Fetch the current value of the given property according to its rendering expression. If the given property has been bound to a rendering expression then evaluate that it and return its value, or null if the property is not bound.

        Note that this is not necessarily the same thing as retrieving the property value from the underlying component itself.

        Returns:
        The bound property value or null if the named property has not been bound when the GUI was built.
        Throws:
        AnyException

        Description copied from class: PropertyAccessMap
        Make a new property binding using the given property set, binding the specified property to the specified object. The property set must be that returned by getPropertySet(o).

        The PropertySet.PropertyBinding class supports the invocation of the set/get methods, however this class does not make any assumptions about threading implications (such as GUI thread safety, for example).
